   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "In this notebook, we will breifly discuss few topics which we will be frequently using in subsequent notebooks. The topics include:  \n",
    "\n",
    "1. Transpilation  \n",
    "2. Executing circuits with: real backend, ideal simulator, and noisy simulator"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "4492db41",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "# Transpilation"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "5e437364",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Transpilation is a step to convert a high-level quantum circuit to a device compatible one. Typically, quantum circuits are written with high-level gates, e.g., 3-qubit+ gates. One the other hand, real quantum computers have a limited set of native gates (basis gates). For example, `ibm_peekskill` supports single-qubit `ID, SX, X, RX, Delay, Reset` and 2-qubit `CX` gates. Moreover, the devices have limited connectivity meaning the native 2q gate is supported between limited set of *connected* qubits, not between any qubits on the device. Thus, we need a compilation step that will convert the high-level non-compliant circuit such that its gates are decomposed into the native gates of the device as well as properly routed (using SWAP operations) to meet the connectivity constraint of the device. This is where transpiler comes into play. A transpiler does the above-mentioned items as well as performs numerous circuit optimizations such as mapping to low-noise qubits, gate cancellation and intelligent routing to reduce gate counts, and so on.\n",
    "\n",
    "As each gate operation is noisy in present day quantum computers, it is paramount to have an optimized version (less gates, less depths, etc.) of the final circuit to combat noise to some extent.\n",
    "\n",
    "Qiskit comes with a built-in compiler (the *transpiler*) which does the above and provides many configuration options. We will discuss the bare minimum options here."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 1,
   "id": "c3c0208a",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "# import the transpile function that performs the transpilation\n",
    "from qiskit import transpile\n",
    "# import function to create random quantum circuit\n",
    "from qiskit.circuit.random import random_circuit\n",
    "\n",
    "# import for fetching a backend\n",
    "from qiskit_ibm_provider import IBMProvider\n",
    "\n",
    "import matplotlib_inline\n",
    "matplotlib_inline.backend_inline.set_matplotlib_formats('retina')"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 2,
   "id": "d25058be",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "# create a random circuit\n",
    "qc = random_circuit(num_qubits=5, depth=3, max_operands=3, measure=True, seed=0)"

  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "57f1c40e",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Fetching backend"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 5,
   "id": "fbe67f45",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "# fetching backend\n",
    "# IBMProvider(token=<>, isntance=<>); token and instance can be found in and copied from your\n",
    "# `https://quantum-computing.ibm.com/account` account\n",
    "# e.g., `instance='ibm-q/open/main'`\n",
    "# you can save your token and load your account next time without writing the token everytime\n",
    "# `IBMProvider.save_account(token='<IBM Quantum API key>')`\n",
    "provider = IBMProvider()\n",
    "backend = provider.get_backend(\"ibm_peekskill\")"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 6,
   "id": "7158d921",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "# bare minimum transpile call\n",
    "# optimization_level=3 implements preset passes\n",
    "transpiled_qc = transpile(qc, backend=backend, optimization_level=3)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 7,

   "source": [

   ]
  },

   "id": "eb05821d",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [

   "metadata": {},

   ]
